'''Emma ʻAʻima Aʻii Nāwahī''' (September 28, 1854 – December 28, 1935) was a [[Native Hawaiian]] political activist, community leader and newspaper publisher. She and her husband [[Joseph Nāwahī]] were leaders in the  [[Opposition to the overthrow of the Kingdom of Hawaii|opposition]] to the [[overthrow of the Kingdom of Hawaii]] and they co-founded ''Ke Aloha Aina'', a [[Hawaiian language]] newspaper, which served as an important voice in the resistance to the annexation of Hawaii to the United States.{{sfn|Silva|1998|page=57}}{{sfn|Silva|2004|page=139}}{{sfn|Kauanui|Kauanui|2008|page=60}} After annexation, she helped established the [[Democratic Party of Hawaii]] and became a supporter of the [[Women's suffrage in the United States|women's suffrage]] movement.

==Early life ==
Born on September 28, 1854, at Kūkūau, a rural part of [[Hilo, Hawaii|Hilo]] on the island of [[Hawaii (island)|Hawaii]], she was regarded as a ''[[hapa|hapa-pākē]]'', of half-[[Native Hawaiian]] and half-[[Chinese immigration to Hawaii|Chinese]] descent.{{sfn|Proto|2009|pages=44–45}}{{sfn|Bennion|1990|page=149}}{{sfn|Kuʻualoha|2002|pages=254–255}} Her mother Kahaoleʻauʻa was the daughter of a minor Hilo chief, while her father Tong Yee was a Chinese immigrant from [[Zhongshan|Xiangshan County]], [[Guangdong]]. Her father originally left China to take part in the [[California Gold Rush]] but later settled in Hilo in 1850 where he became a successful businessman and co-founded Paukaʻa Sugar Plantation with other Chinese sugar planters from lands leased from King [[Kamehameha V]].<ref name="TongYee">{{harvnb|Kai|1974|pages=65–67}}; {{harvnb|Char|Char|1983|page=28}}</ref>{{sfn|Haley|2014|pages=322–323}} Her parents married on June 25, 1851.<ref>{{cite web|author=Hawaiʻi State Archives|year=2006|title=Ai-i–Kahaoleaua marriage record|work=Marriages – Hawaii (1832–1910)|volume=1|page=6|via=Ulukau, the Hawaiian Electronic Library|url=http://ulukau.org/algene/cgi-bin/algene?e=d-001off-algene--00CL1%2e1--2----0--010---4-------0-1l--10en-Zz-1---20-about---00-1-1-00-0-0-000utfZz-8-00&a=d&d=01-000007|accessdate=June 5, 2014}}</ref> Her father adopted the surname ''Aʻii'' (based on the Hawaiian pronunciation of his given name) for himself and his children. She and her four sisters: Aʻana, Aʻlai, Aʻoe, and Mihana were known as ''Ka Pua O Kina'' (The Flower of China) and regarded as "famous beauties."{{sfn|Char|Char|1983|page=28}}<ref>{{cite news|title=Ua halao Mrs. Mihana Kalaniwahine Ai|newspaper=Ka Hoku o Hawaii|location=Hilo|date=April 3, 1928|volume=XXI|issue=43|page=2|url=https://nupepa-hawaii.com/2016/01/03/death-of-mihana-kalaniwahine-ai-1928/|access-date=May 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170910085110/https://nupepa-hawaii.com/2016/01/03/death-of-mihana-kalaniwahine-ai-1928/|archive-date=September 10, 2017|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}</ref>

On February 17, 1881, Emma married politician [[Joseph Nāwahī]], in Hilo, as his second wife.<ref>{{cite web|author=Hawaiʻi State Archives|year=2006|title=Nawahi–Aii marriage record|work=Marriages – Hawaii (1832–1910)|volume=1|page=398|via=Ulukau, the Hawaiian Electronic Library|url=http://ulukau.org/algene/cgi-bin/algene?e=d-001off-algene--00CL1%2e1--2----0--010---4-------0-1l--10en-Zz-1---20-about---00-1-1-00-0-0-000utfZz-8-00&a=d&c=algene&cl=CL1.1&d=01-000401|accessdate=June 5, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150912214039/http://ulukau.org/algene/cgi-bin/algene?e=d-001off-algene--00CL1%2e1--2----0--010---4-------0-1l--10en-Zz-1---20-about---00-1-1-00-0-0-000utfZz-8-00&a=d&c=algene&cl=CL1.1&d=01-000401|archive-date=September 12, 2015|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}</ref> They had three sons: Albert Kahiwahiwa Nāwahī (1881–1904), Alexander Kaʻeʻeokalani Nāwahī (1883–1942) and Joseph Nāwahī, Jr. (1885–1888). Through their sons, they have surviving descendants living to this day.{{sfn|Higashi|Wilson|1999|page=12}}{{sfn|McKinzie|1986|page=64}}<ref>{{cite sign|title=Grave Marker of Joseph Nawahi, Jr. and Mrs. Kahaoleaua|type=|location=Hilo, Hawaii|institution=Homelani Memorial Park}}</ref> They also adopted a daughter named Emmeline Kaleionamoku "Kalei" Nāwahī (1877–1901), who died while attending [[St. Andrew's Priory School]] in Honolulu.<ref>{{cite news|title=Died|newspaper=The Independent|location=Honolulu|date=March 11, 1901|volume=|issue=|page=3|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047097/1901-03-11/ed-1/seq-3/|access-date=May 7, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202062522/http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047097/1901-03-11/ed-1/seq-3/|archive-date=February 2, 2017|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}; {{cite news|title=Death of Miss Nawahi|newspaper=The Pacific Commercial Advertiser|location=Honolulu|date=March 11, 1901|volume=|issue=|page=1|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047084/1901-03-11/ed-1/seq-1/|access-date=May 7, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202062526/http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047084/1901-03-11/ed-1/seq-1/|archive-date=February 2, 2017|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}</ref>
During her husband's political career and the couple's residency in Honolulu, Emma became a [[lady-in-waiting]] and confidante to Queen [[Liliuokalani|Liliʻuokalani]].{{sfn|Proto|2009|pages=44–45}}{{sfn|Bennion|1990|page=149}}

==Political activism==
[[File:Hui Aloha ʻĀina o Na Wahine.jpg|250px|thumb|right|The Hui Aloha ʻĀina o Na Wahine.]]
Following the [[Overthrow of the Kingdom of Hawaii|overthrow of the monarchy]], on January{{nbsp}}17, 1893, her husband Joseph Nāwahī became the president of Hui Aloha ʻĀina o{{nbsp}}Na Kane (Hawaiian Patriotic League for Men), a patriotic group founded shortly after the overthrow to oppose annexation and support the deposed queen. Emma joined the corresponding female organization, the Hui Aloha ʻĀina o{{nbsp}}Na Wahine (Hawaiian Women's Patriotic League), which was under the leadership of [[Abigail Kuaihelani Campbell]] as president.<ref name="SilvaPetition">{{harvnb|Silva|2004|pages=123–163}}; {{cite web|last=Silva|first=Noenoe K.|title=The 1897 Petitions Protesting Annexation|work=The Annexation Of Hawaii: A Collection Of Document|year=1998|publisher=University of Hawaii at Manoa|url=http://libweb.hawaii.edu/digicoll/annexation/petition/pet-intro.php|accessdate=December 19, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161230013831/http://libweb.hawaii.edu/digicoll/annexation/petition/pet-intro.php|archivedate=December 30, 2016|deadurl=yes}}</ref> She served one of the member of the executive committee of the organization in 1893 and later served as the Secretary of the Hilo Branch of the League.{{sfn|Blount|1895|pages=491–492}}<ref name="Michelson1897">{{cite news|last=Michelson|first=Miriam|title=Strangling Hands Upon A Nation's Throat|newspaper=The San Francisco Call|location=San Francisco|date=September 30, 1897|volume=LXXXII|issue=122|pages=1–3|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85066387/1897-09-30/ed-1/seq-1/|accessdate=May 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171126085841/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85066387/1897-09-30/ed-1/seq-1/|archive-date=November 26, 2017|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}</ref>

In 1893, Emma and the other members of the executive committee of Hui Aloha ʻĀina o{{nbsp}}Na Wahine submitted a petition to the United States Commissioner [[James Henderson Blount]] sent by President [[Grover Cleveland]] to investigate the overthrow. The petitions addressed to the government of the United States read:

{{quote|We, the women of the Hawaiian Islands, for our families and the happiness of our homes, desire peace and political quiet, and we pray that man’s greed for power and spoils shall not be allowed to disturb the otherwise happy life of these islands, and that the revolutionary agitations and disturbances inaugurated here since 1887, by a few foreigners may be forever suppressed.<br />
To that effect we believe that, in the light of recent events, the peace, welfare, and honor of both America and Hawaii will be better served, for the present, if the Government of the great American Republic does not countenance the illegal conduct and interference of its representatives here and the rash wish of a minority of foreigners for annexation.<br />
Therefore, we respectfully but earnestly pray that Hawaii may be granted the preservation of its independent autonomy and the restoration of its legitimate native monarchy under our Queen Liliuokalani, in whom we have full confidence.<br />
And we hope that the distinguished citizen, who so wisely presides over the United States, may kindly receive this our petition, for which we shall evermore pray for God's blessing on him and his Government.{{sfn|Blount|1895|pages=491–492}}}}

In December 1894, a search warrant was served on the Nāwahīs' Kapālama home looking for "sundry arms and ammunition." Although nothing was found, Joseph Nāwahī was arrested for treason and bail was set at 10,000 dollars. He spent nearly three months in jail until being bailed out.{{sfn|Proto|2009|page=101}} 
In May 1895, Nāwahī and Emma founded ''Ke Aloha Aina'', a weekly anti-annexationist newspaper written in the [[Hawaiian language]] to promote Hawaiian independence and opposition to American annexation.{{sfn|Silva|1998|page=57}}{{sfn|Silva|2004|page=139}}{{sfn|Kauanui|Kauanui|2008|page=60}}
The paper ran until 1920.{{sfn|Chapin|2000|page=7}}<ref name="KeAlohaAinaTranslated">{{harvnb|Like|Nawahi|Silva|1998|pages=76–105}}; {{harvnb|Like|Nawahi|Silva|2002|pages=118–138}}</ref>

Following his release, Nāwahī's health deteriorated from the [[tuberculosis]] he had contracted during his imprisonment. On the recommendation of his doctor to seek a change of climate, they left Hawaii for a trip to San Francisco, California.{{sfn|Silva|1998|pages=57–58}} They left Honolulu aboard the steamer ''Alameda'' on August 20, 1896, along with the families of [[Edward C. MacFarlane]] and [[Hermann A. Widemann]], both influential royalists and former cabinet ministers of Liliʻuokalani.<ref>{{cite news|title=Local And General News|newspaper=The Independent|location=Honolulu|date=August 19, 1896|volume=|issue=|page=3|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047097/1896-08-19/ed-1/seq-3/|access-date=May 7, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226073907/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047097/1896-08-19/ed-1/seq-3/|archive-date=December 26, 2017|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}; {{cite news|title=Passengers|newspaper=The Hawaiian Gazette|location=Honolulu|date=August 21, 1896|volume=|issue=|page=8|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83025121/1896-08-21/ed-1/seq-8/|access-date=May 7, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226073843/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83025121/1896-08-21/ed-1/seq-8/|archive-date=December 26, 2017|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}; {{cite news|title=Passengers|newspaper=The Hawaiian Gazette|location=Honolulu|date=August 21, 1896|volume=|issue=|page=8|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83025121/1896-08-21/ed-1/seq-8/|access-date=May 7, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226073843/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83025121/1896-08-21/ed-1/seq-8/|archive-date=December 26, 2017|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}; {{cite news|title=The Alameda Always On Time|newspaper=The San Francisco Call|location=San Francisco|date=August 28, 1896|volume=|issue=|page=7|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85066387/1896-08-28/ed-1/seq-7/|access-date=May 7, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226130259/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85066387/1896-08-28/ed-1/seq-7/|archive-date=December 26, 2017|dead-url=no|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On September 14, 1896, Nāwahī died of tuberculosis in San Francisco. According to Silva, his last words were to Emma, apologizing for "taking her so far from the ''‘äina'' and from her family and friends, to deal with his death alone in a foreign place".{{sfn|Silva|1998|pages=57–58}}{{sfn|Silva|2004|page=142}} Emma had the remains of her dead husband embalmed and returned to Hawaii for two grand state funerals organized by his supporters, and burial at their home in Hilo.{{sfn|Silva|2004|page=142}}

After Nāwahī's death, Emma became an important political leader in her own right, continuing the legacy of her husband.<ref>{{cite web|title=Emma Aima Nawahi|work=Women of the West Museum|year=|publisher=Autry Museum of the American West|location=Los Angeles|url=https://theautry.org/explore/exhibits/suffrage/nawahi_full.html|accessdate=May 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100713213514/https://theautry.org/explore/exhibits/suffrage/nawahi_full.html|archivedate=July 13, 2010|deadurl=yes|df=}}</ref> In 1897, Emma and members of both the male and female branches of Hui Aloha ʻĀina collected over 21,000 signatures by the residents of the Hawaiian Islands opposing an annexation treaty being discussed on the floors of the [[United States Senate]]. These [[Kūʻē Petitions]] were submitted by a delegation of Native Hawaiians and was used as evidence of the strong resistance of the Hawaiian community to annexation, and the treaty was defeated in the Senate. After the failure of the treaty, Hawaii was instead annexed by the [[Newlands Resolution]], issued in July 1898, shortly after the outbreak of the [[Spanish–American War]].{{sfn|Haley|2014|pages=317–336}}<ref name="SilvaPetition" />{{sfn|Mehmed|1998|pages=142–143}}

After annexation, Emma helped organize the [[Democratic Party of Hawaii]] in 1899 at the time of the formation of the [[Territory of Hawaii]]. In the 1910s, she became a supporter of the [[Women's suffrage in the United States|women's suffrage]] movement prior to the passage of the [[Nineteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution]] in 1920.{{sfn|Yasutake|2017|pages=120–121, 123–124}}{{sfn|Dennis|Hirschfelder|Flynn|2016|page=667}}

Emma died on December 28, 1935 and was buried at Homelani Memorial Park in Hilo alongside her husband.<ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|title=Noted Figure In Hawaiian History Dies|newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin|location=Honolulu|date=December 28, 1935|volume=|issue=|page=1|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23032424/noted_figure_in_hawaiian_history_dies/|via=Newspapers.com|accessdate=August 16, 2018}}; {{cite news|last=|first=|title=Deaths|newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin|location=Honolulu|date=December 30, 1935|volume=|issue=|page=14|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23032512/deaths_emma_nawahi/|via=Newspapers.com|accessdate=August 16, 2018}}; {{cite news|last=|first=|title=Mrs. Nawahi Dies|newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin|location=Honolulu|date=January 4, 1936|volume=|issue=|page=41|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23032503/mrs_nawahi_dies/|via=Newspapers.com|accessdate=August 16, 2018}}; {{cite news|last=|first=|title=Died|newspaper=The Honolulu Advertiser|location=Honolulu|date=December 29, 1935|volume=|issue=|page=16|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23032480/died_emma_nawahi/|via=Newspapers.com|accessdate=August 16, 2018}}; {{cite news|last=|first=|title=Mrs. E. Nawahi, Hilo Kamaaina, Passes At 86|newspaper=The Honolulu Advertiser|location=Honolulu|date=December 29, 1935|volume=|issue=|page=7|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23032462/mrs_e_nawahi_hilo_kamaaina_passes/|via=Newspapers.com|accessdate=August 16, 2018}}</ref>

