{{india-bio-stub}}

'''Javier Barba-Hernández''' (d. 1986) was a Mexican former lawyer turned enforcer, hired by the [[Guadalajara Cartel]] to combat the Mexican [[Federal Judicial Police]] (FJP) and the American [[Drug Enforcement Administration]] (DEA). 

Hernandez acted as a warlord for [[Ernesto Fonseca Carrillo]], [[Rafael Caro Quintero]] and [[Miguel Ángel Félix Gallardo]]. According to the DEA he is believed to have assisted in the transportation of two Americans, John Walker and Alberto Radelat, who were later killed by the cartel under the false suspicion they were DEA agents. Prior to his death he was wanted for questioning in the murder of DEA agent [[Enrique Camarena Salazar|Enrique Camarena]].<ref name="USCourt">{{cite news|url=http://bulk.resource.org/courts.gov/c/F3/15/15.F3d.833.91-50342.html |author=United States Court of Appeals, Ninth Circuit |title=United States of America v. Javier Vasquez-Velasco |date=November 1, 1993}}</ref><ref name="Organized">{{cite book|title=World Encyclopedia of Organized Crime |pages=45 |first=Jay Robert |last=Nash |year=1993 |isbn=0-306-80535-9 |publisher=De Capo Press}}</ref>

Barba was killed on November 13, 1986<ref name="Organized" /> in a shoot-out with [[Federal Judicial Police|Mexican Federal Judicial Police]] in [[Mazatlán|Mazatlán, Mexico]]. The DEA believes this may be part of a cover-up as the FJP has refused to turn over his fingerprints for identification.<ref name="USCourt" />

