'''John Wentworth Jr.''' (July 17, 1745 – January 10, 1787) was a lawyer who served as a delegate to the [[Continental Congress]] for [[New Hampshire]] and a signer of the [[Articles of Confederation]].
==Biography== He was born to [[John Wentworth (judge)|Judge John Wentworth]] in [[Somersworth, New Hampshire]] in 1745, and is a descendant of "Elder" [[William Wentworth (elder)|William Wentworth]]. He graduated from [[Harvard University|Harvard]] in 1768 before studying law. He moved to [[Dover, New Hampshire]] where he started his practice. His cousin, [[John Wentworth (governor)|Governor Wentworth]], appointed him the probate register for [[Strafford County, New Hampshire|Strafford County]], and he held that post until his death.
He was active in the various revolutionary committees, and was elected to the convention (later the State Assembly) from Dover every year from 1776 to 1780. He was a member of the state council, supporting [[Meshech Weare]], from 1780 to 1784, and was a member of the [[Committee of Safety (American Revolution)|New Hampshire Committee of Safety]]. That committee operated as the revolutionary government when the Assembly was not in session.
In 1778 and 1779, he was selected as one of the delegates to the Continental Congress. His term of service gave him the chance to sign the Articles of Confederation when the Congress passed that plan to unify the colonies. As New Hampshire established a more stable government, he was elected to the State's Senate from 1784 to 1786. He died in Dover and is buried in the [[Pine Hill Cemetery (Dover, New Hampshire)|Pine Hill Cemetery]] there.<ref>{{FAG|7084386}}</ref> His wife and seven children survived him.
